definition.value: An organyl group consisting of a tetrasaccharide of N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues linked sequentially (1->2), (1->3) and (1->2), and linked at the reducing end glycosidically to a 2-[2-(hexanamido)ethylamino]-3,4-dioxocyclobutylaminomethyl group used as a tether for conjugation to proteins.
A glycotriaosylceramide having alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the glycotriaosyl component attached to the Cer(d18:1/18:0).

An organyl group consisting of a hexasaccharide of N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues linked sequentially (1->2), (1->3), (1->2), (1->2)  and (1->2), and linked at the reducing end glycosidically to a 2-[2-(hexanamido)ethylamino]-3,4-dioxocyclobutylaminomethyl group used as a tether for conjugation to proteins.
A glycotriaosylceramide having alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the glycotriaosyl component attached to the Cer(d18:1/20:0).

An organyl group consisting of a hexasaccharide of N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues linked (1->2) throughout, and linked at the reducing end glycosidically to a 2-[2-(hexanamido)ethylamino]-3,4-dioxocyclobutylaminomethyl group used as a tether for conjugation to proteins.
A glycotriaosylceramide having alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the glycotriaosyl component attached to the Cer(d18:1/22:0).
A glycotriaosylceramide having alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the glycotriaosyl component attached to the Cer(d18:1/24:0).
A glycotriaosylceramide having alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the glycotriaosyl component attached to the Cer(d18:1/24:1(15Z)).
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is octadecanoyl.

A one-carbon compound that is methane in which the hydrogens have been replaced by two fluorines, a bromine, and a chlorine. Widely used in 'vapourising liquid'-type fire extinguishers, its use is now generally banned under the Montreal Protocol (ozone-depleting substances), although it is still used in certain applications (e.g. aviation).
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is (15Z)-tetracosenoyl.
A member of the class of  dihydrochalcones that is the 2'-O-methyl derivative of odoratol.
A hydroxamic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from each of the hydroxamic acid groups of desferrioxamine B
A N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group specified is (13Z)-docosenoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both myristoleoyl groups.
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is eicosanoyl.
A beta-D-galactosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is eicosanoyl.
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is docosanoyl.
A beta-D-galactosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is docosanoyl.
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is tetracosanoyl.
A beta-D-galactosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group is specified as tetracosanoyl.

A glycoside consisting of a linear hexasaccharide of N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues linked (1->2) throughout, and linked at the reducing end glycosidically to a 5-(methoxycarbonyl)pentyl group used to facilitate conjugation to proteins.
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is hexacosanoyl.
A D-ornithine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the terminal carboxy groups of two citric acid units with the two amino groups of D-ornithine.
A beta-D-galactosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is hexacosanoyl.
A beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is (17Z)-hexacosenoyl.

An ornithine derivative resulting from reaction of D-ornithine at the amino group, the carboxy group or the side-chain amino group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of D-ornithine by a heteroatom.
A beta-D-galactosyl-(1<->1')-N-acylsphinganine in which the acyl group specified is (17Z)-hexacosenoyl.
A beta-D-glucosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group is specified as hexadecanoyl.
A beta-D-glucosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group is specified as octadecanoyl.
A beta-D-galactosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group is specified as octadecanoyl.
A beta-D-glucosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group is specified as eicosanoyl.
A beta-D-galactosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group is specified as eicosanoyl.
An 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine(1-) in which the 1-acyl group is specified as arachidonoyl.
A hydroxamic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the three hydroxamic acid groups of coelichelin.
A UDP-L-rhamnose in which the rhamnose portion has beta-configuration at its anomeric centre
A UDP-N-acetylmuramoyl-L-alanine(3-) in which the D-muramoyl fragment has alpha-configuration at its anomeric centre.
An amino trisaccharide consisting of alpha-L-fucopyranose, beta-D-galactopyranose and N-acetyl-D-galactopyranosamine residues joined in sequence with a (1->2)- and a (1->3)-linkage, respectively.
Any member of the class of  indoles carrying at least one hydroxy group.
An alkanethiol that is propane substituted by a thiol group at position 1.
A hydroxamic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from each of the hydroxamic acid groups of desferrioxamine E.
A member of the class of 2,5-diketopiperazines obtained by cyclodimerisation of N(5)-acetyl-N(5)-hydroxy-L-ornithine.
An organosulfate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfate group of any hexosylceramide sulfate.
An organosulfate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfate group of any dihexosylceramide sulfate; major species at pH 7.3.
Any iron chelate that consists of a siderophore complexed to iron(III)
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in algae including unicellular organisms like chlorella and diatoms to multicellular organisms like giant kelps and brown algae.

A synthetic 28-amino acid polypeptide consisting of glutaminyl, seryl, prolyl, seryl, tyrosyl, prolyl, alpha-aspartyl, arginyl, alpha-glutamyl, tyrosyl, seryl, alpha-aspartyl, alpha-glutamyl, alpha-aspartyl, arginyl, glutaminyl, isoleucyl, lysyl, glutaminyl, methionyl, leucyl, histidyl, glutaminyl, alpha-glutamyl, cysteinyl, prolyl, arginyl and leucinamide residues joined in sequence. A synthetic version of the peptide epitope from the major peanut allergen glycoprotein Arachis hypogaea h2 (Ara-h2).

A glycoside that is beta-D-xylose in which the hydrogen of the anomeric hydroxy group is replaced by a 4-aminobutyl group. A synthetic version of the beta-xylosyl glycoside (BXG) epitope from the major peanut allergen glycoprotein Arachis hypogaea h2 (Ara-h2).
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four free amino groups of amikacin; major species at pH 7.3.
